<div class="container-narrow" style="margin-top:2rem">
    <div class="card">
        <h3>What is Blazor?</h3>
        <p>
            Blazor enables full end-to-end development in .NET, which helps streamline development and reduces context
            switching between languages.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h3>Where it fits in a system</h3>
        <p>
            Typical stack: <strong>Blazor WASM</strong> (UI) ⇄ <strong>Minimal API / ASP.NET Core</strong> (services) ⇄
            <strong>DB (SQL/NoSQL)</strong> + Auth (Identity/Entra/Magic Link).
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h3>Pros & Cons (at a glance)</h3>
        <ul class="mb-0">
            <li>
                <vscode>+</vscode><strong> Full-stack C#</strong> means no switching languages when building UI + logic
            </li>
            <li>
                <vscode>+</vscode><strong> Component reuse</strong> + robust tooling makes scaling easier
            </li>
            <li><strong><code>–</code> Initial payload</strong> (WASM) can be larger</li>
            <li><strong><code>–</code> JS ecosystem parity</strong> sometimes requires interop</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <h3>Try a live example</h3>
        <p>Open <a href="/counter">Counter</a> to see event handling, two-way binding, and basic validation.</p>
    </div>
</div>